2 TIME SERIES SIMULATION

We can sumulate times series using r command.

2.1 White noise

n<-500
wn<-rnorm(n)
plot.ts(wn,
     col='steel blue',
     main='White noise',
     frame.plot = FALSE
     )

2.2 Random walk

n<-500
rwalk<-cumsum(rnorm(n))
plot.ts(rwalk,
     col='steel blue',
     main='Random walk',
     frame.plot = FALSE
     )

2.3 Another random walk

rwalk2<-cumsum(rnorm(n)+rnorm(n))
plot.ts(rwalk2,
     col='steel blue',
     main='random walk 2',
     frame.plot = FALSE
     )

2.4 Cumulated random walk

rwalk3<-cumsum(cumsum(rnorm(n)))
plot.ts(rwalk3,
     col='steel blue',
     main='cumulated random walk',
     frame.plot = FALSE
     )

rwalk4<-cumsum(cumsum(rnorm(n)+rnorm(n)+rnorm(n)))
plot.ts(rwalk4,
     col='steel blue',
     main='cumulated random walk',
     frame.plot = FALSE
     )

2.5 With a trend

tseries<-1-(1:n)/100+cumsum(rnorm(n))+.2*rnorm(n)
plot.ts(tseries,
        col='steel blue',
        frame=FALSE
        )

x<-(1:n)/100
tseries1<- .3 + .5*cos(2*pi*x) - 1.2*sin(2*pi*x) +
      .6*cos(2*2*pi*x) + .2*sin(2*2*pi*x) +
      -.5*cos(3*2*pi*x) + .8*sin(3*2*pi*x)+0.2*rnorm(n)
  
plot.ts(tseries1,
        col='steel blue',
        frame=FALSE,
        )

3 AUTOCORRELATION

Ttme series observations are not independent, to check the dependence we can use the autocorrelation function. In R the autocorrelation is computed using the acf function.

par(mfrow=c(4,2))
acf(LakeHuron,main='Lake Huron')
acf(wn,main='White noise')
acf(rwalk,main=names(rwalk))
acf(rwalk2,main=names(rwalk2))
acf(rwalk3,main=names(rwalk3))
acf(rwalk4,main=names(rwalk4))
acf(tseries,main=names(tseries))
acf(tseries1,main=names(tseries1))
